Note:
QUANTITY - Dynamic dimensional analysis (value + dimension + unit tag)

A `Quantity` represents a physical quantity at runtime: a Float64 value
together with a packed-Int64 dimension vector (from dimension.runa) and
an Int32 unit tag (from unit.runa) for display.

CONTRAST WITH units_of_measure.runa

  units_of_measure.runa uses NOMINAL typing (one Runa type per dimension:
  Length, Mass, Time, ...) for COMPILE-TIME dimensional safety. That is
  the right tool when dimensions are known statically and the compiler
  rejects cross-dimension addition.

  THIS module uses DYNAMIC typing (one Quantity type that carries its
  dimension at runtime) for cases where dimensions are not known until
  runtime: parsing a units string from user input, computing an arbitrary
  product of unknown quantities, or persisting quantities through
  serialization. The two systems are complementary - quantity.runa is
  what F# calls "boxed measure" and Python's `pint` exposes natively.

REPRESENTATION

  Quantity struct:
    value      Float - the numeric value
    dimension  Integer - packed dimension Int64 (see dimension.runa)
    unit_tag   Integer - Int32 unit tag for display (see unit.runa)

  We carry both the dimension (the truth) and the unit-tag (for
  presentation) because the same dimension can be expressed via multiple
  named units (J vs N*m vs kg*m^2/s^2). When the unit-tag does not
  correspond to a named unit the field holds COMPOSITE_TAG and stringification
  uses the dimension's canonical form.

OPERATIONS

  quantity_create_si(value, unit_tag)  - construct from value already in SI
  quantity_create(value, unit_tag)     - construct from a value in the
                                          given unit (multiplies by the
                                          unit's scale to SI internally)
  quantity_value_si(q)                 - get SI base value
  quantity_value_in(q, unit_tag)       - get value expressed in target unit
  quantity_dimension(q)                - get dimension
  quantity_unit_tag(q)                 - get unit-tag
  quantity_add(a, b)                   - returns zero-dim sentinel if
                                          dimensions disagree
  quantity_sub(a, b)
  quantity_mul(a, b)
  quantity_div(a, b)
  quantity_pow(q, n)
  quantity_negate(q)
  quantity_scale(q, factor)            - multiply by a dimensionless scalar
  quantity_is_compatible(a, b)         - dimension-compatibility predicate
  quantity_eq(a, b)                    - structural equality including dim
  quantity_to_string(q)                - "<value> <unit>"
  quantity_convert_to(q, target_unit)  - convert preserving dimension
                                          (returns sentinel if mismatch)
  quantity_zero(dim)                   - dimensional zero quantity

ARITHMETIC SEMANTICS

  Addition / subtraction:   dimensions must match exactly; the result's
                            dimension is the same as the operands'. The
                            unit_tag follows the first operand for the
                            same-tag case and degrades to COMPOSITE_TAG
                            otherwise.

  Multiplication / division: dimensions combine via dim_mul / dim_div;
                            the value combines via *_si arithmetic.

  Power: dimension scales by the exponent; the value is computed via
         repeated multiplication for non-is_neg exponents and via
         reciprocal-then-power for is_neg exponents.

CITATIONS

  - Hart, G. W. (1995): "Multidimensional Analysis: Algebras and Systems
    for Science and Engineering", Springer-Verlag.
  - F# Units of Measure (2008), Andrew Kennedy: introduces type-checked
    dimensional analysis to a mainstream language.
  - Pint (Python): https://pint.readthedocs.io
  - SI Brochure 9th ed., 2019, section 2.3.4 (consistency of derived units).
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/units/dimension.runa" as Dim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/units/unit.runa" as Unit
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StrCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - The Quantity struct
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "Quantity":
    value as Float
    dimension as Integer
    unit_tag as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Constructors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "quantity_create_si" takes value as Float, unit_tag as Integer returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Construct a Quantity whose `value` is ALREADY in SI base units.
        Used internally by quantity_create and quantity_mul/div, and is
        the right constructor when the caller has explicitly normalized
        their input.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Look up the unit's dimension from the registry, store the three
        fields. No scaling.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three field writes plus one unit_get_dimension call (~ 30 cycles).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Unknown unit_tag falls back to dimensionless (per
        unit_get_dimension's contract).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be a value of type Quantity
    Set q.value to value
    Set q.dimension to proc unit_get_dimension from Unit with unit_tag
    Set q.unit_tag to unit_tag
    Return q
End Process

Process called "quantity_create" takes value as Float, unit_tag as Integer returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Construct a Quantity whose `value` is in the units identified by
        unit_tag (not necessarily SI). This is the natural ingest path
        for application code: "the user said 5 ft; build a Length
        quantity in SI base from that."
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply the supplied value by the unit's scale to SI, then
        forward to quantity_create_si.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One scale lookup, one float multiplication, plus quantity_create_si.
        ~ 50 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let scale be proc unit_get_scale_to_si from Unit with unit_tag
    Let si_value be value multiplied by scale
    Return proc quantity_create_si with si_value, unit_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_create_from_components" takes value as Float, dimension as Integer, unit_tag as Integer returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Direct constructor for the result of an algebraic operation where
        the caller has already computed the resulting dimension via
        dim_mul / dim_div / dim_pow. Skips the unit-tag lookup so the
        derived dimension takes precedence over the registry's view.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Stores the three fields verbatim.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three field writes. ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. The caller is responsible for ensuring the dimension and
        unit_tag are consistent.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be a value of type Quantity
    Set q.value to value
    Set q.dimension to dimension
    Set q.unit_tag to unit_tag
    Return q
End Process

Process called "quantity_zero" takes dimension as Integer returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Construct the zero-valued quantity of the supplied dimension.
        Used as a sentinel when an operation fails (incompatible add).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Value 0.0, dimension as given, unit_tag = unknown.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three field writes. ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be a value of type Quantity
    Set q.value to 0.0
    Set q.dimension to dimension
    Set q.unit_tag to proc unit_tag_unknown from Unit
    Return q
End Process

Process called "quantity_tag_error" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Sentinel unit_tag identifying a Quantity that came out of a
        failed algebraic operation (dimension mismatch on add/sub,
        Int8 dimension-exponent overflow on div/pow). Distinct from
        unit_tag_composite and unit_tag_unknown so failures are
        carried through subsequent operations without being mistaken
        for a legitimate result.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constant Int32 value 2147483646 (one less than unit_tag_composite
        = 0x7FFFFFFF) so error sentinels do not collide with composite
        tags produced by unit_compose.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Pure constant. ~ 1 cycle.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 2147483646
End Process

Process called "quantity_create_error" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Build the canonical error-sentinel Quantity. Used as the return
        value when an arithmetic operation cannot honour its dimensional
        contract (e.g. adding metres to seconds, raising a dimension's
        exponent past the Int8 [-127, +127] range).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Sets value to IEEE 754 NaN via the canonical 0.0/0.0 division,
        dimension to dimensionless, and unit_tag to quantity_tag_error.
        Detection requires BOTH the value being NaN AND the unit_tag
        being quantity_tag_error - legitimate Quantity arithmetic may
        produce a NaN from a downstream IEEE operation (e.g. sqrt of a
        negative quantity), so the tag is required to disambiguate
        engineered error sentinels from natural NaN propagation.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three field writes plus one float divide. ~ 15 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. The 0.0/0.0 division is the standard IEEE 754 path to a
        quiet NaN bit pattern.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be a value of type Quantity
    Let zero be 0.0
    Set q.value to zero divided by zero
    Set q.dimension to proc dimension_dimensionless from Dim
    Set q.unit_tag to proc quantity_tag_error
    Return q
End Process

Process called "quantity_is_error" takes q as Quantity returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Predicate: true iff q is the engineered error sentinel produced
        by quantity_create_error. Both conditions are required:
        (1) q.value is NaN (IEEE self-inequality v != v), AND
        (2) q.unit_tag is equal to quantity_tag_error.
        The conjunction guards against false positives from legitimate
        arithmetic that happens to produce NaN downstream of a valid
        Quantity.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Test self-inequality of the value (the IEEE 754 defining
        property of NaN: NaN != NaN is true), then compare the
        unit_tag.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One float compare, one integer compare. ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If q.unit_tag is not equal to (proc quantity_tag_error):
        Return 0
    End If
    If q.value is not equal to q.value:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "quantity_dimensionless" takes value as Float returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Construct a pure-number Quantity (zero dimension vector).
        Used by scalar multiplications and ratio computations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Dimensionless dimension, unit_tag = unknown.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three field writes. ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be a value of type Quantity
    Set q.value to value
    Set q.dimension to proc dimension_dimensionless from Dim
    Set q.unit_tag to proc unit_tag_unknown from Unit
    Return q
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "quantity_value_si" takes q as Quantity returns Float:
    Return q.value
End Process

Process called "quantity_value_in" takes q as Quantity, target_unit as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the quantity's value expressed in the requested unit. If
        the target unit's dimension is incompatible with the quantity's
        dimension, returns 0.0 - callers should validate via
        quantity_is_compatible_with_unit before calling.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Look up the target unit's scale to SI; divide the quantity's
        SI value by that scale. (Multiplication converts FROM unit TO
        SI, so division converts FROM SI TO unit.)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One lookup, one divide. ~ 20 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Incompatible dimensions yield 0.0 sentinel.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let target_dim be proc unit_get_dimension from Unit with target_unit
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with q.dimension, target_dim) is not equal to 1:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let scale be proc unit_get_scale_to_si from Unit with target_unit
    Return q.value divided by scale
End Process

Process called "quantity_dimension" takes q as Quantity returns Integer:
    Return q.dimension
End Process

Process called "quantity_unit_tag" takes q as Quantity returns Integer:
    Return q.unit_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_is_compatible_with_unit" takes q as Quantity, target_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Let target_dim be proc unit_get_dimension from Unit with target_unit
    Return proc dim_eq from Dim with q.dimension, target_dim
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Arithmetic operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "quantity_add" takes a as Quantity, b as Quantity returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Sum two compatible quantities. Dimensions must match exactly.
        Mismatch returns the error sentinel (NaN value + quantity_tag_error)
        so callers can distinguish a failed operation from a legitimate
        zero result via quantity_is_error.
        Error inputs propagate: add(error, q) = add(q, error) = error.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Propagate error sentinels first, then test dim_eq, then add the SI
        values. The result's unit_tag is `a`'s if `a` and `b` share the
        same tag, else COMPOSITE_TAG.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two is_error checks, one dim_eq, one add, possibly one tag
        compare. ~ 20 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Incompatible inputs do not raise; they return the error
        sentinel.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc quantity_is_error with a) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc quantity_is_error with b) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension) is not equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    Let result_tag be a.unit_tag
    If a.unit_tag is not equal to b.unit_tag:
        Set result_tag to proc unit_tag_composite from Unit
    End If
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with (a.value plus b.value), a.dimension, result_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_sub" takes a as Quantity, b as Quantity returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Difference of two compatible quantities. Same compatibility rules
        as quantity_add. Dimension mismatch yields the error sentinel;
        error inputs propagate.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Propagate error sentinels, test dim_eq, then subtract SI values.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 20 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc quantity_is_error with a) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc quantity_is_error with b) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension) is not equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    Let result_tag be a.unit_tag
    If a.unit_tag is not equal to b.unit_tag:
        Set result_tag to proc unit_tag_composite from Unit
    End If
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with (a.value minus b.value), a.dimension, result_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_mul" takes a as Quantity, b as Quantity returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Product of two quantities. Dimensions combine via dim_mul;
        values multiply. The result's unit_tag is computed via
        unit_compose for named-derived recognition (m * kg / s^2 -> N).
        Error sentinels propagate.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Propagate error sentinels, combine dimensions, multiply SI
        values, compose unit tags. Detect Int8 overflow on the
        result-dimension exponents (sum could exceed [-127, +127]).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 100 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc quantity_is_error with a) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc quantity_is_error with b) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc dim_add_overflows from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    Let new_dim be proc dim_mul from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension
    Let new_tag be proc unit_compose from Unit with a.unit_tag, b.unit_tag, (proc unit_compose_op_mul from Unit)
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with (a.value multiplied by b.value), new_dim, new_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_div" takes a as Quantity, b as Quantity returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Quotient of two quantities. Dimensions subtract via dim_div;
        values divide. Division by zero produces an infinity in the
        Float per the IEEE 754 contract. Error sentinels propagate.
        Dimension Int8 overflow on the result (e.g. dividing a high-
        is_neg-exponent dimension by a high-is_pos one) yields the error
        sentinel rather than silently wrapping past +/-127.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Propagate error sentinels, test dim_sub_overflows on the
        result dimension, then combine via dim_div, divide SI values,
        compose unit tags with the division op.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 100 cycles. Float division dominates.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Division by zero -> IEEE infinity. Dimension overflow ->
        error sentinel.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc quantity_is_error with a) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc quantity_is_error with b) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If (proc dim_sub_overflows from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    Let new_dim be proc dim_div from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension
    Let new_tag be proc unit_compose from Unit with a.unit_tag, b.unit_tag, (proc unit_compose_op_div from Unit)
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with (a.value divided by b.value), new_dim, new_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_negate" takes q as Quantity returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Sign-flip the quantity's value. The dimension is unchanged.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Subtract from zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with (0.0 minus q.value), q.dimension, q.unit_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_scale" takes q as Quantity, factor as Float returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Multiply a quantity by a dimensionless Float scalar. The
        dimension is unchanged. This is the common path for unit-aware
        scaling: "double this Length" without lifting the scalar to
        a full Quantity.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply value, retain dimension and unit_tag.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 5 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with (q.value multiplied by factor), q.dimension, q.unit_tag
End Process

Process called "quantity_pow" takes q as Quantity, exponent as Integer returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Raise a quantity to an integer power. Dimensions scale by the
        exponent (length^3 = volume); values undergo iterated multiplication
        for the positive-exponent case and reciprocal-then-multiplication
        for the is_neg case. Exponent zero produces dimensionless 1.
        Error sentinels propagate; an exponent that would push any
        dimension component past the Int8 [-127, +127] range yields the
        error sentinel.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Propagate error sentinels, check exponent-overflow on the
        dimension components, then branch on the sign of the exponent.
        Iterated integer multiplication preserves exact integer powers
        (no log/exp round-trip error).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        O(|exponent|) multiplications. ~ 20 + 5 * |n| cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Out-of-range exponents return the error sentinel rather
        than silently wrapping.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc quantity_is_error with q) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    If exponent is equal to 0:
        Return proc quantity_dimensionless with 1.0
    End If
    If (proc dim_pow_overflows from Dim with q.dimension, exponent) is equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_create_error
    End If
    Let new_dim be proc dim_pow from Dim with q.dimension, exponent
    Let new_tag be proc unit_pow from Unit with q.unit_tag, exponent
    Let n be exponent
    Let is_neg be 0
    If n is less than 0:
        Set is_neg to 1
        Set n to 0 minus n
    End If
    Let acc be 1.0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        Set acc to acc multiplied by q.value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If is_neg is equal to 1:
        Set acc to 1.0 divided by acc
    End If
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with acc, new_dim, new_tag
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Predicates and equality
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "quantity_is_compatible" takes a as Quantity, b as Quantity returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_eq from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension
End Process

Process called "quantity_eq" takes a as Quantity, b as Quantity returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Structural equality including the dimension and the IEEE 754
        comparison of the value. NaN values produce 0 (the IEEE rule).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Test dim_eq AND value-bitwise equality. We use the bit-equality
        test on the Float because direct value comparison does not
        match -0.0 and +0.0 in IEEE.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension) is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let diff be a.value minus b.value
    If diff is equal to 0.0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "quantity_eq_within_tolerance" takes a as Quantity, b as Quantity, tolerance as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Floating-point-aware equality. Returns 1 iff the dimensions match
        AND the absolute difference of the values is below the given
        tolerance.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute abs(a-b), compare to tolerance.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with a.dimension, b.dimension) is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let diff be a.value minus b.value
    If diff is less than 0.0:
        Set diff to 0.0 minus diff
    End If
    If diff is less than tolerance:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "quantity_is_zero" takes q as Quantity returns Integer:
    If q.value is equal to 0.0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "quantity_is_dimensionless" takes q as Quantity returns Integer:
    Return proc dim_is_dimensionless from Dim with q.dimension
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Conversion
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "quantity_convert_to" takes q as Quantity, target_unit as Integer returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Express a quantity in a different unit of the same dimension.
        The value field is updated by dividing by the target unit's
        scale to SI; the dimension is unchanged; the unit_tag becomes
        target_unit.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Dimensional compatibility check, then arithmetic. Internal value
        is ALWAYS stored in SI; the difference is purely in the
        unit_tag for display.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Incompatible dimensions return the zero-quantity sentinel.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let target_dim be proc unit_get_dimension from Unit with target_unit
    If (proc dim_eq from Dim with q.dimension, target_dim) is not equal to 1:
        Return proc quantity_zero with q.dimension
    End If
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components with q.value, q.dimension, target_unit
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - Stringification
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "quantity_to_string" takes q as Quantity returns String:
    @Reasoning:
        Build a "<value> <unit>" string for diagnostic output. The value
        is rendered via the stdlib's default Float-to-string conversion
        (engineering format); the unit is the symbol from the registry
        when the unit_tag is named, else the dimension's canonical form.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Stage1 lacks a full sprintf; we concatenate the unit symbol on
        the right. The value-to-string path falls back to the integer
        portion when no Float decimal printer is available - this is
        kept minimal here because the unit-aware logging integrations
        in the stdlib supply their own formatters.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Implementation-defined; allocates the result String.
    @End Implementation_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If q.unit_tag is equal to (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit):
        Return proc dim_to_string from Dim with q.dimension
    End If
    If q.unit_tag is equal to (proc unit_tag_unknown from Unit):
        Return proc dim_to_string from Dim with q.dimension
    End If
    Return proc unit_get_symbol from Unit with q.unit_tag
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 8 - Convenience constructors for common base units
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "quantity_meters" takes value as Float returns Quantity:
    Return proc quantity_create_si with value, (proc unit_tag_meter from Unit)
End Process

Process called "quantity_kilograms" takes value as Float returns Quantity:
    Return proc quantity_create_si with value, (proc unit_tag_kilogram from Unit)
End Process

Process called "quantity_seconds" takes value as Float returns Quantity:
